After the liberal international order
Cambridge—Many analysts believe that the liberal international order ended with China's rise and the election of Donald Trump as U.S. president.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he strive to revive it?
Perhaps the outcome was not that, but he must find some alternative.
Critics point out that the U.S. order since 1945 was neither global in nature nor always very liberal.
It excluded more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and incorporated many authoritarian states.
American hegemony has always been exaggerated.
Although the most powerful countries must take the lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided — and Americans will therefore suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example.
A realistic goal of the Biden administration should be to establish an international system based on rules, with different member states participating in handling different matters.
Will China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and 21st century, both countries were unable to balance U.S. power, while the U.S. pursued the promotion of liberal values above the sovereignty of states.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without the approval of the UN Security Council.
It also supported the 2005 United Nations General Assembly resolution on "responsibility to protect," aimed at providing protection for citizens suffering from severe abuse by their own governments — and the United States later used this principle in 2011 to justify bombing Libya in order to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as American arrogance after the Cold War — for example, when the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to regime change, Russia and China felt betrayed — while defenders of the action describe it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
In any case, the growth in power of China and Russia has more strictly constrained liberal interventionist actions.
What remains then?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty stipulated in the UN Charter, which states that a state may only wage war for self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the forcible occupation of neighboring territories has been rare, and once it occurs, it incurs significant costs through sanctions (as seen in Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
In addition, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled states, while political cooperation has also successfully curbed the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of a rule-based order remains critically important.
In terms of economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Long before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will lead to the decoupling of global supply chains, especially when national security is threatened.
Although China criticizes the United States for preventing companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the U.S. position is consistent with sovereignty claims.
In any case, China has prevented Google, Facebook, and Twitter from operating in China for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
At the same time, despite the outbreak of this current crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
In contrast, interdependence in the ecological field has created insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereignty, as threats transcend national boundaries.
No matter how economic globalization faces setbacks, environmental globalization will continue, as it is subject to biological and physical laws, which are unaffected by contemporary geopolitical logic.
The above issues threaten everyone, but no country is capable of solving them independently.
In issues such as the 2019 COVID-19 pandemic and climate change, power also possesses what is called a positive-sum dimension.
Under such premises, merely thinking about exercising power over others is insufficient.
We must also think in terms of exercising power jointly with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization are beneficial to us and others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, this has not affected Sino-U.S. cooperation.
The challenge Biden faces is whether the United States and China can cooperate to produce global public goods while competing in traditional great-power domains.
The cyberspace is a new and important issue — — as it is partially transnational in nature but also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has already been partially fragmented.
Rules for internet freedom of speech and privacy can be established within democratic countries, but these rules would not be recognized by authoritarian states.
As suggested by the Global Commission on Internet Governance, if authoritarian regimes also wish to achieve connectivity, certain rules prohibiting the alteration of the basic structure of the internet would also be in their interest.
But when they use proxies to conduct information warfare or interfere in elections (a practice that violates sovereignty), norms must be reinforced through rules such as those negotiated during the Cold War to limit escalation in maritime incidents, even though ideological hostility remains.
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly declare the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrence.
Upholding the liberal values in cyberspace does not mean the United States unilaterally disarms.
In contrast, the United States should differentiate between permissible open persuasion using soft power and covert information warfare as hard power, and when the other side launches covert information warfare, the United States is obligated to respond.
It is permissible for Russia and China to publicly broadcast programs and radio broadcasts, but covert actions such as manipulating social media to achieve unification are not allowed.
And the United States will continue to criticize these countries' human rights records.
Public opinion polls show that the American public wants to avoid military intervention but does not want to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values these values.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the liberal international order.
The issue is whether the United States can cooperate with its core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while simultaneously working with a broader range of countries to manage rule-based international systems needed to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemic outbreaks, cyberattacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
